## 1. Longest Common Substring

Find the longest substring that appears in both strings **contiguously**.

### DP Table Approach
```
         ""  a  b  c  d  a  f
      "" [0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0]
      z  [0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0]
      b  [0, 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0]
      c  [0, 0, 0, 2, 0, 0, 0]
      d  [0, 0, 0, 0, 3, 0, 0]
      f  [0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1]
```

```java
// dp[i][j] = length of LCS ending at s1[i-1] and s2[j-1]
// Time: O(m*n) | Space: O(m*n)
public static String longestCommonSubstring(String s1, String s2) {
    int m = s1.length(), n = s2.length();
    int[][] dp = new int[m + 1][n + 1];
    int maxLen = 0, endIndex = 0;

    for (int i = 1; i <= m; i++) {
        for (int j = 1; j <= n; j++) {
            if (s1.charAt(i - 1) == s2.charAt(j - 1)) {
                dp[i][j] = dp[i - 1][j - 1] + 1;
                if (dp[i][j] > maxLen) {
                    maxLen = dp[i][j];
                    endIndex = i; // end of LCS in s1
                }
            } else {
                dp[i][j] = 0; // must be contiguous — reset!
            }
        }
    }
    return s1.substring(endIndex - maxLen, endIndex);
}
```

### Space-Optimized (O(n)):
```java
// Time: O(m*n) | Space: O(n)
public static int longestCommonSubstringLength(String s1, String s2) {
    int m = s1.length(), n = s2.length();
    int[] prev = new int[n + 1];
    int maxLen = 0;

    for (int i = 1; i <= m; i++) {
        int[] curr = new int[n + 1];
        for (int j = 1; j <= n; j++) {
            if (s1.charAt(i - 1) == s2.charAt(j - 1)) {
                curr[j] = prev[j - 1] + 1;
                maxLen = Math.max(maxLen, curr[j]);
            }
        }
        prev = curr;
    }
    return maxLen;
}
```

### Test Cases:
```
s1 = "abcdef", s2 = "bcdf"  → "bcd" (length 3)
s1 = "ABCBDAB", s2 = "BDCAB" → "AB" (length 2)
s1 = "xyz", s2 = "abc"       → "" (length 0)
```

